body:
## Description

DisputePrinciples extracted from user responses are currently only injected into the LLM prompt as hints. The LLM can ignore them, and when semantic dedup overflows, there's no safety net. Findings that contradict established trust boundaries get posted anyway.

## Proposed Solution

- Add a post-semantic-dedup filtering stage in `poster.go`
- Check each finding against DisputePrinciples
- If finding's category matches `DoNotFlag` AND context matches `AppliesTo`, skip it
- Zero LLM cost, runs after semantic dedup as final safety net

## Implementation Approach

```go
// filterByDisputePrinciples removes findings that contradict established principles.
func filterByDisputePrinciples(
    findings []PostableFinding,
    principles []domain.DisputePrinciple,
) (filtered []PostableFinding, skipped int) {
    for _, f := range findings {
        if contradictsPrinciple(f, principles) {
            skipped++
            log.Printf("principle filter: skipped %s finding in %s (contradicts trust boundary)",
                f.Category, f.File)
            continue
        }
        filtered = append(filtered, f)
    }
    return filtered, skipped
}

// contradictsPrinciple checks if a finding contradicts any dispute principle.
func contradictsPrinciple(f PostableFinding, principles []domain.DisputePrinciple) bool {
    for _, p := range principles {
        if containsIgnoreCase(p.DoNotFlag, f.Category) {
            if matchesContext(f, p.AppliesTo) {
                return true
            }
        }
    }
    return false
}
```

## Files to Modify

- `internal/usecase/github/principle_filter.go` - NEW: filtering logic
- `internal/usecase/github/principle_filter_test.go` - NEW: tests
- `internal/usecase/github/poster.go` - Wire filtering into post flow
- Need to pass `ThemeExtractionResult` through to poster

## Complexity

Medium - requires fuzzy matching logic for AppliesTo/DoNotFlag patterns.

## Context

Part of defense-in-depth against review noise at scale. See [platform#78](https://github.com/delightfulhammers/platform/pull/78) analysis.

This is the final safety net in the deduplication pipeline - if a finding makes it past fingerprint dedup and semantic dedup, this stage catches trust boundary violations (e.g., "prompt injection from internal data" when user has disputed similar findings).

## Test Cases

1. Finding matching DoNotFlag + AppliesTo → skipped
2. Finding matching DoNotFlag only → passed through
3. Finding matching AppliesTo only → passed through
4. Case-insensitive matching works
5. Partial string matching in file paths works
6. Empty principles list → all passed through
